g.text: Components of Kafka:
1. Kafka Broker/Server:
- First server that users interact with.
- It is listening to some Port(9092) to accept connections.
2. Low-Level APIs (Abstractions):
- Producer API
- produces content to the broker
- via Raw TCP Connection: so Broker can send info to Producer, Producer can send info to broker.
- Consumer API
- consumes content from the broker
- via Raw TCP Connection: so Broker can send info to Producer, Producer can send info to broker.
3. Topics:
- Logical Partitions where you write contents to.
- Append only (delete is not allowed)
Here consumer starts polling to get data from topic in kafka server.
So its not push model in Kafka.
In RabbitMQ, Broker pushes messages to Consumer.
Topics contain append only list of messages.
Topics may grow large, what do we do when data grows large (millions)?
- we do sharding
e.g. user id 1 to 1,000,000 go to Database 1.
user id 1,000,000 to 2,000,000 to Database 2.
Complexity: But as you introduce sharding, now producers and consumers have to know what is a partition, in addition to Topic;
to read and write from.
This is fast, because we work with indexes and partitions.
There is no string matching etc, adhoc queries like RDBMS.

Explanation
Use Cases
1. Queue: Message published once, consumed once.
2. PubSub: Message published once, consumed many times.
How can we do both using Kafka?
Answer: Consumer Groups (abstraction)
Consumer Groups:
* Invented to do parallel processing on partitions-> Can run and consume data parallel from multiple partitions.
* It removes awareness of a consumer from partition i.e. sits in between
- If in Group 1 (Consumer Group), only one consumer is there say Consumer 1, then it will consume from All partitions (1, 2, 3 ...) in Users Topic.
- If we add one more consumer C2 in Group1 CG, then CG rebalances the partition - now C1 consumes from Partition1, C2 from Parition 2.
- One partition will be consumed by only one consumer.
- A consumer can consume from multiple partitions, say C2 can consume from Partition 2, 3, ... and C1 can consume from Partition 1, 4 ..
- In given diagram, Consumer 3 cannot join Group1 CG because, we have only 3 partitions.
- In given diagram, parallel consumption from Parition1 and 2 will happen via C1 and C2. The system behaves like Queue. 1 Partition -> 1 Consumer.
To act like a Queue -> Put all your consumers in one Consumer Group.
To act like a pub/sub -> Put each consumer in its unique group. -> A partition can be consumed by multiple consumers in different CGs.
Kafka is Distributed System? How?
- In Kafka, if there are two server/brokers - they use Leader / Follower pattern at Partition Level.
- This is useful for when a machine goes down, we dont lose all the data.
- Where is the data stored about Leader / Follower?
- i.e. 9092 is the leader of Partition 1 on Users Topic.
- 9093 is the leader of Partition 2 on Users Topic.
-> ZOOKEEPER -> It caused lot of pain than benefits.

PROS
1. Append Only Commit Log. You always know where the end is of queue. Its extememly fast, unlike Databases using B Tree, Fragmentation etc
- Then it logically materialises differently for your usecase.
2. Performance:
- Reads are very fast. As we just work with positions and partitions.
- Seeking a position is extremely fast e.g. Sector 5 Block 5 and read data from disk.
3. Distributed:
- With zookeeper, you can distribute partitions, but one partition will be leader across distribution.
- Easily scalable.
4. Long Polling:
- Kafka Uses Pull Model.
- Consumers have to do polling, and dont respond with empty messages, wait for sometime.
If there are 700 bytes of messages or 7 messages or some data available, push it to consumer. This prevents consumer from not blocking on CPU cycles, only connection is open.
5. Event-Driven (micro-services), Pub/Sub and Queue.
- Pub/Sub can be a broadcast message for various services (Redis, ETL etc, or loyalty, order, etc) by keeping such consumers in different consumer groups.
6. Scalable:
- Just add more Kafka Brokers. Zookeeper will pick it up.
7. Parallel Processing:
- 1 Topic :: multiple partitions -> 1 CG many consumers, can consume in parallel.
- Overhead on producer side :- Producer needs to know partition, which sucks for application.
Note: RabbitMQ uses Push Model - Limitation: Consumers cannot sometimes consume as fastly as producers produce.
Consumers don't have cycles to consume.
CONS
1. Zookeeper at scale behaves badly for micro-services - maintenance is hard.
2. Producer explicit partition can lead to problems.
3. Complex to install, configure & manage.
Every broker on a Kafka cluster is also named a Bootstrap Server.
All brokers have the metadata required for the clients (producer or consumer) to discover brokers.
When a client connects to one of the brokers (which are already configured as bootstrap servers in the Kafka configuration) it makes a "metadata request".
The response includes information about topics, partitions, leader brokers, etc.
Once the client gets this info, then - in the case of a producer - it makes the write request directly to the leader broker for that specific partition.
While consuming, if consumer is in CG, Zookeeper automatically assignes a partition, so we dont have to mention partition to consume from.
Just Topic is sufficient.
